So in this scenario, air resistance is definitely a factor.


01:00:59.500 --> 01:01:02.960
And the stretch of the spring and its restoring force


01:01:02.960 --> 01:01:04.460
is definitely a factor.


01:01:04.460 --> 01:01:06.100
But here's the interesting part.


01:01:06.100 --> 01:01:08.220
During the first phase of the jump,


01:01:08.220 --> 01:01:11.480
while the bungee cord is not yet stretching,


01:01:11.480 --> 01:01:13.200
but it is uncoiling,


01:01:13.200 --> 01:01:15.580
because it starts out in a great big U shape,


01:01:15.580 --> 01:01:17.220
it's dangling down,


01:01:17.220 --> 01:01:22.220
and it has to unravel or unwrap itself as you are falling.


01:01:22.420 --> 01:01:24.780
The first model that you probably think of


01:01:24.780 --> 01:01:26.820
is that it's just free fall,


01:01:26.820 --> 01:01:30.060
that you are being pulled by the force of gravity


01:01:30.060 --> 01:01:33.260
and the bungee cord is being pulled by the force of gravity.


01:01:33.260 --> 01:01:36.220
And so there's no net interaction between the two.


01:01:36.220 --> 01:01:37.860
And so you would think it would be just,


01:01:37.860 --> 01:01:39.900
your acceleration would be equal to G,


01:01:39.900 --> 01:01:42.140
9.8 meters per second squared.


01:01:42.140 --> 01:01:44.060
